        "dc:description": "Conventionally, evaporites are defined as chemical sediments precipitated during solar heating of brine, with precipitative mineralogies linked to the ionic proportions in its mother brine and to atmospheric chemistry. Conceptually, what defines evaporite sediments is broad, with a general theme that the rock is precipitated initially by solar heating and concentration of a surface or near-surface brine. Other than solar-induced heating, salt saturation can be attained by brine cooling (prograde salt) or freezing (cryogenic salt), non-solar heating (retrograde salt) or \u201csalting out\u201d at a variety of chemical interfaces (mixing or transition salts) in hydrothermal and diagenetic settings. Marine evaporite mineralogies have evolved as the chemistry of the ocean has evolved. Early Archean marine salts are enriched in bicarbonate minerals such as nahcolite and trona, reflecting a reducing CO2-CH4 Archean atmosphere. With the transition to a more oxygenated atmosphere around 2.3Ga, sulfate, not sulfide, became a significant component in the world's oceans. This oxygenation of the ocean and the atmosphere is reflected in common occurrences of gypsum/anhydrite beds, or their pseudomorphs, and dissolution breccias, in saline sediments of this age. Since that time, the ionic proportions in the world's ocean evolved to approach those seen in the Phanerozoic. Across the Phanerozoic, the proportions of the primary marine bittern salts (sylvite, carnallite, kainite) oscillate in concert with changes in the Mg/Ca ratio and sulfate levels in an evolving ocean.",
